comment.body:
@Thegreenmage: I remember using an Asus Netbook 1005HA for this exact purpose a few years ago. That was a heap of doodoo but I loved it to bits. Must have written a million words on it. There are much better options now. 

I like the idea of a tablet and a keyboard for some reason, but I just know that if I got something that had some grunt to it, I'd never get anything done because I would spend my time doing the same things I normally do on my laptop or desktop. Which is nothing useful, unfortunately.

If only something like a Thinkpad X61 with a 10-12 hour battery life and 2 pound weight existed!

@SSDifnskdjfnsdjk: Yep, 8GB will work for some people, my mum absolutely slays it with a Q9550 Core 2 Quad and 8 GBs of RAM, but she pretty much only uses Word and Powerpoint on that thing.

The real problem with 8GBs is not the sheer amount, it's that that's the base amount on premium business / multimedia laptops. A new, from Lenovo T14 fresh off their website goes for $1799 with 8 gigs soldered, no upgrade. The first step that comes with 16gb is $2799, and that's just not good enough. It's not good enough to begin with, but it's not upgradeable so double nope. Apple does it and that makes my eye twitch.

All the latitudes, ideapads, acer swifts etc, in the $500-$1000 range can come with 8 GBs for those who want a dependable, albeit mid-range laptop. For the premium range, let's step up to 16GBs already, it's been time for three years :D

@Maycontainnuts: heya, thanks a lot for that, I've just seen the message. Will read up and see what I can do! :) I've no pictures of the EliteBook, if I ever get to put my paws on one I'll take it to a billion pieces and take photos of it. Current lineup is Lenovo and dell stuff mostly :)
Heard of Luis Rossman, I think he's the kind of guy who has an attitude but can back it up with being right most of the time. Cool guy. I think hardware people buy should become their property. Software... not necessarily but the hardware I should be able to do with as I damn well please once I've paid for it.
(I also think software should become fair game if the original maker no longer maintains it. Like a copyright expiry or something after a few years)
